JT stated the pallet looks to have become unstable and fell over during transit causing a one 5 gallon pail to become damaged on the botto m of the pallet. JT stated the damaged pail looks to have been crushed causing a spill of 64oz of the UN1760, CORROSIVE LIQUIDS, N.O.S on the trailer floor. JT stated one of the dock workers started to re stack the pallet on a new skid and JT advised he told the dock worker to stop work and he was g oing to call the spill into safety. JT stated the spill was made possible from improper blocking embracing.~

column63: Conveyer or Material Handling Equipment Mishap
column169: On 10/2/2024 at approximately 1245, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 393838 at the ramp facility in Fort Worth,  reporting a dangerous goods spill.  The shipment consisted of one fiberboard box that contained 4 glass bottles of petroleum crude oil.  The package was damaged by mechanical equipment, resulting in one of the glass bottles breaking and spilling.   There is no secondary containment or positive closure.  The cushioning between the bottles was insufficient.  The broken glass and damaged outer package were placed in a salvage drum for proper disposal and the remaining bottles were placed in a separate drum, awaiting an amended Shipper's Declaration for futher transport.

column63: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column169: XPO Logistics terminal XMI experienced a UN2815 Aminoethylpiperazine-HP release from a 55-gallon poly drum. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 25-gallons of product released to an 8' x 15' area of the trailer floor and a 6' x 28' area of the concrete and asphalt lot below. The drum was punctured by a pallet nail puncture. The damaged drum was placed into a 95-gallon poly overpack. Absorbents and simple green were then utilized to clean the impacted areas. All impacted absorbents, pallet wood, and cleanup debris were containerized into (3) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.
